		   <br><nobr><span id=notbold>Score</span>: Excellent [5.00]</nobr><br><br /><a href="/cgi-bin/pm.pl?action=addtolist&addname=Parttime&type=Address" id="fs8"><img src="/shared/plus.gif" border="0" align="middle" height="9" width="9" alt="Add to address book"> Add to address book</a><br /><img src="/shared/transp.gif" width="135" border="0" height="1"></td><td valign="top" class="mform" width="100%"><p>Currently I am playing an Iksar SK.&nbsp;&nbsp;I don't get to play a bunch because real life is always calling.  So, when I do get an opportunity to play I am usually soloing due to time constraints.  I have found that this particular combination is a lot of fun.  Here is why:<br><br>1.) Regeneration - Less time sitting, more time inflicting pain.<br><br>2.) The Iskars have the best newbie zones and quests in the game.  The curscale armor quest is not only a good quest, but serves as a handy knap sack as well.  And you get a reasonable newbie weapon when you start from one of your guild masters.<br><br>3.) Well rounded stats.  Although you don't have the str. of the Ogre or Troll...or the Int. of the DE or Eudites...the initial stats of the Iskar SK are such that you won't have much trouble bumping any of them to more impressive levels.  (I would however suggest sticking a majority of points into the Intel. column.)<br><br>Add a pet into the mix at 9th level.  You will have a character that will be a great help within a group or is able to run around the wilds on it's own with ease.<br><br>Hope this helped...<br><br>Strikke <br>Shadowknight of the 12th Rank<br>Bristlebane</p><span class=sm>----------------------------</span><br>Shrikke - Knight of Fear<br>Bristlebane</td></td></tr><tr><td colspan="2" class="mform"><table border=0 cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0 width="100%"><tr><td id=fs8></td><td align=right id=fs8 >1 Replies</td></tr></table><table width="100%"><tr><td class=mhback>&nbsp;</td><td class=mhback >Thread Subject</a></td><td class=mhback>Star